@Elfansoer very carefully
you can't target items directly, but you can build a hack around it
function CheckSpotForItem(point, radius) local items = Entities:FindAllInSphere(point, radius) for _,item in pairs(items) do -- print(item:GetName(), item.GetContainedItem and item:GetContainedItem():GetName(), (item:GetAbsOrigin() - point):Length()) if item.GetContainedItem then return item end end -- print("CheckSpotForItem | No Item Found", point) return nil end function ability:OnCast(keys) local point = keys.target_points[1] local item = CheckSpotForItem(point, SEARCH_RADIUS) if item then DoStuffToItem(item) end end
pseudo-ish code copied from ours
(i'm assuming you have to do this kind of trick on the assumption that we would have done it the clever way if it were possible, maybe there's a really easy solution)
essentially items that are visible on the ground are entities for which the GetContainedItem attribute/method/key is defined (and returns a handle to the "actual" item represented by the treasure chest or whatever) (edited)
we have a library thingy for casting spells on items directly in your inventory, too, but it's suuuper buggy

if you tell them to go to Vector(0,0,0) for example, they may end up at Vector(0,0.0001,0) and your code will not continue if only checking if they are at the 0,0,0
so just check if they get close enough
